SA, where they would “troll” him and his panelists through questions intended to unveil what Groypers saw as the mainstream conservative movement’s failings, such as its support of [Israel](https://www.britannica.com/place/Israel). After [Kirk’s assassination](https://www.britannica.com/event/Assassination-of-Charlie-Kirk) in September 2025, there was speculation that the [alleged](https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/alleged) shooter, Tyler Robinson, might be a member of the Groyper Army. Indeed, among the first to raise the possibility were Groypers themselves, who recognized that evidence left at the scene—as well as photos in Robinson’s [social media](https://www.britannica.com/topic/social-media) history—indicated that Robinson was steeped in the same Internet meme [culture](https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/culture) that informed much of the Groypers’ online vocabulary. Investigators did not report any connection between Robinson and the Groypers, however, and Fuentes responded to the shooting by declaring, “To all of my followers: if you take up arms, I disavow you. I disown you in the strongest possible terms.”\nAfter Trump’s loss to [Joe Biden](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Joe-Biden) in the [2020 presidential election](https://www.britannica.com/event/United-States-presidential-election-of-2020), Fuentes became prominently involved in the “Stop the Steal” movement, the aim of which was to stop Biden from “stealing” the election. There is no evidence that Fuentes stormed the [U.S. Capitol](https://www.britannica.com/topic/United-States-Capitol) during the [January 6 attack](https://www.britannica.com/event/January-6-U-S-Capitol-attack), but he attended Trump’s speech before the event and encouraged others to enter the building. Despite his defense of Trump, Fuentes was not embraced by mainstream conservatives: After a 2022 dinner at [Mar-a-Lago](https://www.britannica.com/topic/Mar-a-Lago) attended by Trump, Fuentes, and [Kanye West](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Kanye-West), mainstream conservatives, including [Mitch McConnell](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Mitch-McConnell), [Kevin McCarthy](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Kevin-McCarthy-politician), and Trump’s former vice president, [Mike Pence](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Mike-Pence), spoke out against Fuentes.\nA second [iteration](https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/iteration) of the Groyper War took place in 2024, when Fuentes urged his followers to criticize Trump’s presidential campaign on [X](https://www.britannica.com/money/Twitter) (formerly Twitter) and [Truth Social](https://www.britannica.com/topic/Truth-Social), hoping to push Trump’s political platform further to the right. Fuentes celebrated Trump’s election with a repudiation of the [reproductive rights](https://www.britannica.com/topic/pro-choice-movement) slogan “My body, my choice” with a post on X that read: “Your body, my choice. Forever.” During Trump’s second term Fuentes continued to criticize the president on issues of immigration and foreign affairs, as well as Trump’s refusal to release [files](https://www.britannica.com/topic/The-Epstein-Files-A-Timeline) related to [Jeffrey Epstein](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Jeffrey-Epstein). Historically, Fuentes has clashed with other prominent conservative figures such as [Tucker Carlson](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Tucker-Carlson) and [Candace Owens](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Candace-Owens). He apparently achieved a rapprochement with Carlson, however, as Fuentes was featured in a friendly, wide-ranging interview on Carlson’s podcast in October 2025.\n\n Quick Facts\n\n In full:\n Nicholas Joseph Fuentes\n\n Born:\n August 18, 1998 (age 27)\n\n The trusted destination for professionals, college students, and lifelong learners.\n\n [SUBSCRIBE](https://premium.britannica.com/premium-membership/?utm_source=premium&utm_medium=inline-cta&utm_campaign=redesign-2026)\n\nFuentes has faced continual challenges publishing his content, with many social platforms such as X and [Facebook](https://www.britannica.com/money/Facebook), payment platforms like [Venmo](https://www.britannica.com/money/peer-to-peer-payment-overview) and [PayPal](https://www.britannica.com/money/PayPal), and streaming platforms including [YouTube](https://www.britannica.com/topic/YouTube) and [Twitch](https://www.britannica.com/topic/Twitch-service) suspending him (though X [reinstated](https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/reinstated) his account under [Elon Musk](https://www.britannica.com/money/Elon-Musk)’s ownership).\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"77c8177c1d3bb2e1\">>>"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1772851759956}}
